    "85896083": {
      "title": "Life history and abundance of the predaceous psammophilous mayfly Pseudiron centralis McDunnough (Ephemeroptera: Heptageniidae)",
      "abstract": "Aspects of the life history and abundance of Pseudiron centralis McDunnough were examined in the Sand River in east central Alberta. The population exhibited a univoltine summer life cycle, spending 9 to 10 months of the year in the egg stage. Eggs were large (0.33 × 0.41 mm; mean dry weight, 0.005 mg). Larvae were associated with three types of substrate in the river bed: shifting sand, marginal sand, and gravelly sand. Larvae were active epibenthic predators, feeding primarily on psammophilous chironomid larvae. Larval density was low (< 4 larvae/m2); however, larval mortality also appeared to be low. Stage III and IV larvae exhibited a random dispersion pattern. Annual production (instantaneous growth method) was estimated to be 28.70 and 11.24 mg∙m−2∙year−1 in 1980 and 1981, respectively. The relatively large size of first-instar larvae may allow them to cope with the dynamics of sandy substrates, or may be the minimum size that can effectively capture and consume chironomid larvae. Although chironomi..."
    }
